  "Question": "<p><strong>The Problem:</strong> Suppose that <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_592\"><math alttext=\"Z\\thicksim\\text{Poisson}(\\lambda)\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Z</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><merror class=\"ltx_ERROR undefined undefined\"><mtext>\\thicksim</mtext></merror><mo>\u2062</mo><mtext>Poisson</mtext><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>\u03bb</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span>. Find the expected value of <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_593\"><math alttext=\"\\dfrac{1}{1+Z}.\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>Z</mi></mrow></mfrac></mstyle><mo>.</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></p> <p>We have that <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_594\"><math alttext=\"\\begin{aligned} \\displaystyle E\\left[\\frac{1}{1+Z}\\right]&amp;\\displaystyle=\\sum_{% k=0}^{\\infty}\\frac{1}{1+k}\\frac{e^{-\\lambda}\\lambda^{k}}{k!}=e^{-\\lambda}\\sum_% {k=0}^{\\infty}\\frac{\\lambda^{k}}{(k+1)!}=\\frac{e^{-\\lambda}}{\\lambda}\\left[% \\sum_{k=0}^{\\infty}\\frac{\\lambda^{k}}{k!}-1\\right]\\\\ &amp;\\displaystyle=\\frac{e^{-\\lambda}}{\\lambda}[e^{\\lambda}-1]=\\frac{1}{\\lambda}-% \\frac{e^{-\\lambda}}{\\lambda},\\end{aligned}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mtable columnspacing=\"0pt\" rowspacing=\"0pt\"><mtr><mtd columnalign=\"right\"><mrow><mi>E</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo>[</mo><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>Z</mi></mrow></mfrac></mstyle><mo>]</mo></mrow></mrow></mtd><mtd columnalign=\"left\"><mrow><mi></mi><mo>=</mo><mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><munderover><mo largeop=\"true\" movablelimits=\"false\" symmetric=\"true\">\u2211</mo><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn